  CORE ARGUMENT: Introduces the concept of epistemic injustice, identifying two forms: testimonial injustice (when identity prejudice causes deflated credibility judgments) and hermeneutical injustice (when gaps in collective interpretive resources disadvantage marginalized groups in understanding their experiences). Argues these wrongs are distinctively epistemic—harming people specifically in their capacity as knowers—and proposes testimonial justice as an epistemic virtue to counteract them.

  RELEVANCE: Foundational work establishing the framework used throughout this domain. Directly relevant to literature review ethics because citational practices involve credibility judgments about whose testimony (scholarship) deserves inclusion and attention. The testimonial injustice concept illuminates how prejudice-driven exclusion from bibliographies wrongs authors as epistemic agents. The hermeneutical dimension addresses how marginalized perspectives may lack recognition as legitimate knowledge contributions.

