  CORE ARGUMENT: Documents systematic epistemic injustice in global health bioethics through empirical analysis of knowledge production patterns. Shows Global South epistemologies, theories, and experiences are silenced through three mechanisms: who produces knowledge (predominantly Global North institutions/scholars), what theories are applied (Western philosophical frameworks presented as universal), and whose voices are sought (Global South populations studied but not consulted as epistemic authorities). Proposes comprehensive remedies emphasizing structural change, not just inclusion.

