  RELEVANCE: Reveals debates and refinements around foundational framework. Fricker's defense of distinctively epistemic character of epistemic injustice is relevant to whether citational exclusion constitutes epistemic wrong or merely ethical failing. Her emphasis on active critical reflection (not just passive absence of bias) suggests citational justice requires reflexive examination of one's bibliographic choices. The engagement with critics shows epistemic injustice framework is contested, not settled doctrine.

  POSITION: Defense and clarification of virtue epistemology approach. Maintains that individual epistemic virtues are central to addressing epistemic injustice while acknowledging structural dimensions.
  },
  keywords = {epistemic-injustice, testimonial-justice, virtue-epistemology, Medium, INCOMPLETE, no-abstract}
}

@article{Davis2016typecasts,
  author = {Davis, Emmalon},
  title = {Typecasts, Tokens, and Spokespersons: A Case for Credibility Excess as Testimonial Injustice},
  journal = {Hypatia},
  year = {2016},
  volume = {31},
  number = {3},
  pages = {485--501},
  doi = {10.1111/hypa.12251},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Extends Fricker's framework by arguing credibility excess (not just deficit) can constitute testimonial injustice. When speakers from marginalized groups are assigned excess credibility on identity-related topics (as "spokespersons" for their group), this wrongfully reduces them to their identity and burdens them with representational labor. Discusses three patterns: typecasting (assumption that identity determines perspective), tokenism (exceptional individual treated as representative), and spokesperson burden (expectation to speak for entire group). All harm speakers as individual knowers.

  RELEVANCE: Highly relevant to citation practices and literature review ethics. Shows that simply increasing citation of marginalized scholars can perpetuate injustice if done in identity-reductive ways (citing women only on gender, scholars of color only on race, etc.). Illuminates how "diversity" in bibliographies can still enact epistemic injustice if it tokenizes or typecast authors. Suggests citational justice requires recognizing scholars as individuals with diverse expertise, not merely as group representatives.

  POSITION: Expansion of Fricker's framework. Argues testimonial injustice is broader than credibility deficit. Maintains focus on individual harms while addressing group-level patterns.
  },
  keywords = {testimonial-injustice, credibility-excess, identity-prejudice, feminist-epistemology, Medium},
  abstract = {Miranda Fricker maintains that testimonial injustice is a matter of credibility deficit, not excess. In this article, I argue that this restricted characterization of testimonial injustice is too narrow. I introduce a type of identity‐prejudicial credibility excess that harms its targets qua knowers and transmitters of knowledge. I show how positive stereotyping and prejudicially inflated credibility assessments contribute to the continued epistemic oppression of marginalized knowers. In particular, I examine harms such as typecasting, compulsory representation, and epistemic exploitation and consider what hearers are obligated to do in response to these injustices. I argue that because epistemic harms to marginalized knowers also arise from prejudicially inflated assessments of their credibility, the virtue of testimonial justice must be revised to remedy them.},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
}

@article{Pohlhaus2014discerning,
  author = {Pohlhaus, Jr., Gaile M.},
  title = {Discerning the Primary Epistemic Harm in Cases of Testimonial Injustice},
  journal = {Social Epistemology},
  year = {2014},
  volume = {28},
  number = {2},
  pages = {99--114},
  doi = {10.1080/02691728.2013.782581},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Critiques Fricker's claim that primary harm of testimonial injustice is epistemic objectification (treating speaker as mere object/informant rather than knower). Argues primary harm is better understood as derivatization—treating someone as derived/dependent rather than autonomous epistemic agent. Emphasizes that testimonial exchanges are mutual, requiring active participation from both speaker and hearer; derivatization violates this mutuality by denying speaker's epistemic agency and autonomy.

  RELEVANCE: Relevant to understanding how citational practices can wrong authors as epistemic agents. If citing someone's work while systematically misrepresenting or decontextualizing it treats them as mere information source (objectification), or if citing only to critique without genuine engagement denies their autonomous epistemic standing (derivatization), this constitutes testimonial injustice. The emphasis on mutuality suggests literature reviews must engage work cited, not merely extract from it.

  POSITION: Feminist epistemology emphasizing relationality and mutual epistemic engagement. Critical refinement of Fricker's objectification account while maintaining focus on epistemic agency.
  },
  keywords = {testimonial-injustice, epistemic-agency, objectification, derivatization, Medium},
  abstract = {This article examines the primary epistemic harm of testimonial injustice, or, as defined by Miranda Fricker, the injustice of perceiving another epistemic agent as less credible due to an identity prejudice. I first analyze Fricker's account of the harm, which she posits in terms of a subject/object relation as "epistemic objectification." My analysis, however, shows that (1) testimonial injustice does not render its victim to an object-like status and (2) testimonial injustice necessarily treats its victim as a subject, albeit a truncated subject. Drawing on the work of Ann Cahill and Simone de Beauvoir, I demonstrate that the primary harm of testimonial injustice is more aptly described in terms of a subject/other relation, or a relation that circumscribes the subjectivity of its victim within the confines of the perpetrator's subjectivity. Using these conceptual resources to examine the primary epistemic harm of testimonial injustice not only avoids the problems I raise with the notion of epistemic objectification, but also greatly enhances our understanding of testimonial injustice, and consequently of what more epistemically just relations look like.},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
}

@article{Carmona2021silencing,
  author = {Carmona, Carla},
  title = {Silencing by Not Telling: Testimonial Void as a New Kind of Testimonial Injustice},
  journal = {Social Epistemology},
  year = {2021},
  volume = {35},
  number = {5},
  pages = {577--592},
  doi = {10.1080/02691728.2021.1887395},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Introduces "testimonial void"—when a speaker withholds epistemic materials from a hearer-to-be based on faulty assumption that hearer lacks capacity to use them epistemically. Unlike Dotson's testimonial smothering (speaker withholds due to anticipated prejudice from hearer), testimonial void involves speaker's own prejudice about hearer's epistemic capacities. This is a form of silencing where would-be knowers are denied access to testimony due to prejudice. Shows testimonial injustice can be enacted by speakers, not just hearers.

  RELEVANCE: Relevant to literature review practices when scholars withhold their work from certain venues/audiences based on prejudiced assumptions about those audiences' epistemic capacities (e.g., assuming certain scholars/communities cannot engage with sophisticated arguments). Also relevant to accessibility issues in academic writing—when scholars deliberately write inaccessibly based on faulty assumptions about who merits access to knowledge. Illuminates bidirectional nature of testimonial injustice in scholarly communication.

  POSITION: Extension of testimonial injustice framework. Shows speakers can also be wrongdoers in testimonial injustice (not only victims). Emphasizes epistemic trust and relational equality dimensions.
  },
  keywords = {testimonial-injustice, testimonial-void, silencing, epistemic-trust, Medium},
  abstract = {ABSTRACT In this paper, I characterize a new kind of testimonial injustice (TI), a phenomenon I call ‘testimonial void’ (TV), which involves a substantial extension of the limits of the original concept put forward by Miranda Fricker. TV occurs when a speaker withholds epistemic materials on the basis of an epistemically and ethically faulty assumption that a hearer-to-be lacks the capacity to do anything epistemically relevant with them. As in testimonial smothering (TS), testimony is not proffered owing to an anticipated failure of uptake. However, unlike in cases of TS, the anticipated failure of uptake in TV is due to prejudice on the speaker’s part. By comparing TV with other forms of TI, I show that TV shares TI’s conceptual structure and harms. I argue that TV: a) shows the speaker to be a potential wrongdoer, b) reveals that TI cannot be equated with biased credibility assessments, c) entails both an indirect yet extreme form of silencing and d) the failure to extend a kind of epistemic trust implied by the enjoyment of epistemic relational equality. In addition, I explore intricate cases in which TV interacts with TS, identifying smothered instances of TV, as well as non-culpable cases of TV.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{McGlynn2020objects,
  author = {McGlynn, Aidan},
  title = {Objects or Others? Epistemic Agency and the Primary Harm of Testimonial Injustice},
  journal = {Ethical Theory and Moral Practice},
  year = {2020},
  volume = {23},
  pages = {831--845},
  doi = {10.1007/s10677-020-10078-z},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Defends Fricker's objectification account of testimonial injustice's primary harm against Pohlhaus's derivatization alternative. Argues that enriching conception of epistemic objectification (drawing on Martha Nussbaum's cluster analysis) better captures harms than othering/derivatization framework. Shows cases where epistemic agency is affirmed but credibility unjustly impugned can still be understood as objectification when using nuanced account. Maintains objectification framework while acknowledging othering may offer supplementary resources.

  RELEVANCE: Contributes to understanding what makes citational exclusion or misrepresentation a distinctive epistemic wrong. If primary harm is objectification (reducing author to mere information source, denying epistemic agency), this explains why proper citation requires genuine engagement—not just formal attribution. Suggests citational justice requires recognizing cited authors as epistemic agents with autonomous contributions, not mere sources to extract from.

  POSITION: Defense of refined objectification account. Maintains Fricker's basic framework while enriching conceptual resources. Virtue epistemology approach.
  },
  keywords = {testimonial-injustice, objectification, epistemic-agency, virtue-epistemology, Medium},
  abstract = {This paper re-examines the debate between those who, with Miranda Fricker, diagnose the primary, non-contingent harm of testimonial injustice as a kind of epistemic objectification and those who contend it is better thought of as a kind of epistemic othering. Defenders of the othering account of the primary harm have often argued for it by presenting cases of testimonial injustice in which the testifier’s epistemic agency is affirmed rather than denied, even while their credibility is unjustly impugned. In previous work, I have instead argued that such cases suggest that we need to enrich our conception of epistemic objectification in ways encouraged by Martha Nussbaum’s cluster analysis of objectification. Here I continue to make the case for this approach, and I consider the othering account in more detail. I focus in particular on Gaile Pohlhaus Jr.’s arguments for a version of the othering account in terms of the notion of derivatization, which turns on the idea that only such an account can enable us to properly understand the harms of testimonial injustice, in particular the ways in which it interferes with a subject’s epistemic agency and autonomy, and I’ll argue that such arguments should not sway us. Finally, I’ll further support my contention that it is illuminating and helpful to think of the primary harm of testimonial injustice in terms of epistemic objectification, though I will concede that the notion of epistemic othering may offer further helpful resources for understanding how subjects can be harmed by testimonial injustice.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{Nyamnjoh2023what,
  author = {Nyamnjoh, Ari and Ewuoso, Cornelius},
  title = {What Type of Inclusion Does Epistemic Justice Require?},
  journal = {Journal of Medical Ethics},
  year = {2023},
  volume = {49},
  pages = {341--342},
  doi = {10.1136/jme-2023-109091},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Responds to Pratt and de Vries's account of epistemic justice, probing nuances of "inclusion" as remedy for epistemic injustice. Questions whether inclusion should operate within binary North/South vocabulary, whether inclusion can paradoxically produce exclusion (through tokenism or elite capture), and whether inclusion as "politics of belonging" creates new epistemic harms through authenticity demands. Warns that increasing representation without transforming underlying epistemic structures may create appearance of inclusion while leaving exclusion intact (internal exclusion).

  RELEVANCE: Critical analysis directly relevant to debates about citational justice and diversity in literature reviews. Warns that simply including more scholars from Global South (or other marginalized groups) may not achieve epistemic justice if underlying power structures remain. The concept of "internal exclusion" (being formally included but substantively marginalized) applies to tokenistic citation practices. Elite capture warning relevant to concerns about who gets to represent marginalized perspectives in bibliographies.

  POSITION: Postcolonial/decolonial critique of liberal inclusion approaches. Emphasizes need for structural transformation, not just numerical representation. Skeptical of whether epistemic justice can be achieved through inclusion within existing frameworks.
  },
  keywords = {epistemic-justice, inclusion, decolonization, global-south, elite-capture, Low},
  abstract = {Bridget Pratt and Jantina de Vries have made an insightful contribution to enhancing epistemic justice in global health ethics. Their elaboration details intellectual (external) exclusion— described as nonrepresentation—across three levels, and at its core, proposes inclusion to rectify this. To extend this work, we contend that it is worth probing the nuances and challenges associated with inclusion as a response to epistemic injustice. These include (A) the meaning of inclusion outside binary vocabularies of north and south; (B) the possibility of forms of inclusion that produce exclusion and (C) inclusion as a politics of belonging with intellectual confinement as a possible epistemic harm. How the problem of injustice is described influences the substantive meaning of inclusion. In describing epistemic injustice, north and south (centre and periphery) are used as relational markers of power, inclusion, authority and exclusion. While this binary vocabulary is seductive, it can appear to confer proprietary rights to the concepts, theories and values described as originating in the global north (and south). However, such inscriptions of ownership are not always a correct reading of the problem. Sometimes, the ostensible westernness and nonwesternness of ideas are taken for granted, particularly when histories of connection and exchange go unacknowledged. Even if we grant that an idea has its geodiscursive origin in the global north, there is the separate issue of whether it is ever fully constituted in this epistemic location. Therefore, while Pratt and de Vries are right to seek the representation of voices and debates that position themselves as southern, epistemic justice can also entail abandoning the presumption of discrete intellectual traditions by illuminating histories of interaction, exchange and connection, although in unequal encounters. This frames inclusion as an effort in reclamation and appropriation, inscribing Africa and the global south in the genealogy and intellectual history of ideas routinely taken for granted as northern. A second set of issues relates to whether including scholarship from the global south necessarily means that these perspectives are more heard. Sometimes, inclusion can be an instrument of exclusion, a way of (un)consciously weakening the radical claims being pursued. This erosion can occur through internal exclusion, which is the experience of exclusion by individuals positioned as included/represented. This shows that exclusion and inclusion are not always binaries. Increasing visibility through representation of previously excluded knowers and knowledge systems that fit the social descriptions of prime targets for inclusion may enhance optics but direct attention away from the phenomenon of exclusion itself. To consolidate inclusion that matters, internal exclusion should be central to an understanding of exclusion. In order to mitigate the appearance of inclusion, it is important to scrutinise, for example, the language of ‘standards’ and associated processes of establishing epistemic authority, as sites of internal exclusion. Although we lack the space to provide details, this more transformative inclusion regards the epistemologies that are accounted for in the construction of what is meaningful in global health ethics. In addition to which priorities are favoured and by whom, the inclusion that matters involves unravelling the politics of knowledge (production and conversion), particularly in relation to how standards are (re) influenced, (re)developed, (re)validated and fed into the priorities and discourses constitutive of global health ethics. Rather than an exhaustive statement on what constitutes inclusive practices, Pratt and de Vries’ contribution should be taken as impetus to think and rethink inclusion and epistemic justice. The denuding of inclusion can also occur through elite capture, which is ‘the control over the political agendas and resources by a group’s most advantaged people.’ Elite capture points to the possibility that those likely to be included/ deferred to are insufficiently representative of the material conditions and intellectual concerns of the locations they are expected to represent. More cynically, outcomes like elite capture render grammars of inclusion, like epistemic justice, as nothing more than campaigns for parochial power and esteem. Pratt and de Vries do pay some attention to this by effectively outlining epistemic justice as having beneficiaries outside academic elites. As such, epistemic justice would need to be seen as an ongoing commitment to being accountable and responsive to those who are not yet in the room by deliberately cultivating the ‘practical and material bases for popular power over knowledge production and distribution.’ Finally, it is worth paying attention to the politics of belonging that often accompanies the pursuit of inclusion. On a practical level, including voices and perspectives from the global south means making political and ethical judgements about what counts as knowledge from the global south and who qualifies for recognition as African/southern. This means generating values by which membership is judged, such that a key issue becomes the very boundedness of a particular epistemic location. Do these values broaden or constrict the canvass on which southern/ African ideas are painted? Do they constrain or expand the possibilities for negotiating inclusion? While Pratt and de Vries foreground the question of ‘where is knowledge from the global south’, the equally salient question of who/what is recognised as southern lurks around the corner. The political nature of belonging is evident, for example, in the suggestion that one may be from the south geographically but not intellectually. An interest in voices that think from a southern/African location, we imagine, would involve generating criteria of what those voices sound like, and this is inevitably a normative project. With this comes the possibility of an altogether new epistemic harm within the talk of inclusion, whereby expectations of authenticity work to enclose and confine southern scholars within a narrow set of themes, concepts, debates and intellectual traditions.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{Aberg2023how,
  author = {{\AA}berg, Ingrid Birgitta},
  title = {How the Notion of Epistemic Injustice Can Mitigate Polarisation in a Conversation about Cultural, Ethnic and Racial Categorisations},
  journal = {Journal of Philosophy of Education},
  year = {2023},
  doi = {10.1093/jopedu/qhad061},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Examines Kevin Kumashiro's argument that transformative anti-oppressive education requires altering harmful citational practices. Identifies two shortcomings: high discursive literacy prerequisite, and risk of conflating honest mistakes with willful ignorance, leading to polarization. Proposes applying epistemic injustice framework to grant nuanced credit to speakers' intentions, potentially mitigating polarization. Argues attention to outcome (impact) and intention should not be oppositional—both perspectives can inform each other.

  RELEVANCE: Addresses how attention to citational practices as sites of oppression can become polarizing if it fails to distinguish degrees of culpability. Relevant to debates about whether and how to call out problematic citation practices in literature reviews without creating defensiveness that blocks progress. The emphasis on balancing outcome-focus with intention-recognition suggests citational justice advocacy must calibrate criticism carefully. Shows epistemic injustice framework can function as bridge rather than weapon.

  POSITION: Pragmatic approach seeking to balance critical attention to citational harms with pedagogical effectiveness. Emphasizes context-specificity and nuance in attributing epistemic injustice.
  },
  keywords = {epistemic-injustice, citational-practice, education, polarization, Low},
  abstract = {
  abstract_source = {s2},
 It is a common contention that education done uncritically and unreflectively may serve to sustain and justify the status quo, in terms of mechanisms of cultural or racial privileging and marginalization. This article explores an argument made from within anti-oppressive education theory and advocated by theorist Kevin Kumashiro, namely that transformative education must entail altering harmful citational practices. I see two shortcomings in relation to this argument: first, its focus on discursive practice entails a prerequisite of high discursive literacy. Second, it may lead to a failure to give credit to people’s intentions, risking a conflation of honest mistakes and wilful ignorance, and depriving us of theoretical nuance. While a well-argued and important call, I argue in this article that both shortcomings lead to the risk of a polarized conversation. Focusing on cultural, ethnic and racial categorization, and using social studies as an illustration, it is suggested that applying notions from the theoretical concept of epistemic injustice may open up a space for granting nuanced credit to people’s intentions, thereby mitigating the risk of polarization. Rather than viewing attention to outcome and attention to intention as oppositional to one another, it is argued that both theoretical perspectives may benefit from the insights of the other. By applying needed context-specificity and nuance to categorizations of dominance and marginalization in individual discursive exchange, this can be done without granting priority to the experience of dominantly situated knowers.},
}

@article{Taswell2022epistemic,
